76561198069883026,Recommended,301120,19610558,"Posted: 10 December, 2015",all,Cola Galch,"The Good ;- The simulation engine is much better. Scores are more realistics and player statistics after a season are more like real life.- In the real NHL speed is pretty much around the same for all players except a select few who have incredible speed or are really slow. In game most players have speed ratings difference of ~10 except a couple of players (Hagelin, Kreider).- In game ratings are mostly well balanced and are very close to that of the real life player. (Note that ratings can be changed with a 3rd party freeware).- Drafting is very nice having good players in most drafts lets you get good prospects on a yearly basis.- Player development is good. Keep in mind that you need good coaching staff with the rating ""working with youngster"" high enough for the prospect to develop well.The Bad ;- Trading is awefull, Wanting to trade my Stamkos, i was offered a 2nd round pick and two 3rd round picks by all of the teams that had interest into him, Same goes when trying to trade for a player. EG : I needed a first line key winger and i had a surplus of Key 1-2 defender. I offered Subban for Kessel and they did not want to negotiate, so just out of curiosity i add four 1st round picks and they still would not want any part of it. Overall trading needs to be tweeked but you can get a steal every now and then when a team is desperate or overly incompetent.- Way to many injury blows or long term injury. At one point in my game, Galchenyuk, Subban, Price and Pacioretty had over 3 months injury. the longest was Price with 8 months. This to say, i was left with an AHL team in my hands."
